revision.text:
{{wiktionary|Capability}}
A '''Capability''', in the systems engineering sense, is defined as the ability to execute a specified course of action. A capability may or may not be accompanied by an intention.<ref>"Department of Defense Dictionary of Military and Associated Terms", Joint Publication 1-02, DoD, 17 March 2009 {{cite web|url=http://www.dtic.mil/doctrine/jel/new_pubs/jp1_02.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-10-01 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081123014953/http://www.dtic.mil/doctrine/jel/new_pubs/jp1_02.pdf |archivedate=2008-11-23 |df= }}</ref> The term is used in the [[defense industry]] but also in [[private industry]] (e.g. [[Gap analysis]]).
==Capability Gap Analysis== The [[Joint Capabilities Integration Development System]] is an important part of [[United States Department of Defense|DoD]] [[military planning]]. The "Operation of the JCIDS" introduces a Capability Based Analysis (CBA) process that includes identification of capability gaps.<ref>"Operation of the Joint Capabilities Integration and Development System (JCIDS)", [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]] (CJS), CJCS Manual 3170.01, 24 June 2003 [http://www.dtic.mil/cjcs_directives/cdata/unlimit/m317001.pdf]</ref> In essence, a Capability Gap Analysis is the determination of needed capabilities that do not yet exist.<ref>Antommarchi, Sidney N., "A Process for Modeling and Simulation Capability Gap Analysis", [[Interservice/Industry Training, Simulation and Education Conference]] (I/ITSEC), December 2008 [https://archive.is/20120713191442/http://ntsa.metapress.com/app/home/contribution.asp?referrer=parent&backto=issue,6,140;journal,1,12;linkingpublicationresults,1:113340,1]</ref><ref>Antommarchi, Sidney N., "Enhancing and Expanding the Modeling & Simulation Composability Paradigm", 08S-SIW-067, [[Simulation Interoperability Standards Organization]] (SISO), April 2008 {{cite web |url=http://www.sisostds.org/index.php?tg%3Dfileman%26idx%3Dget%26id%3D2%26gr%3DY%26path%3DSimulation+Interoperability+Workshops%2F2008+Spring+SIW%2F2008+Spring+SIW+Papers+and+Presentations%26file%3D08S-SIW-067.doc |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-07-08 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090610030705/http://www.sisostds.org/index.php?tg=fileman |archivedate=2009-06-10 |df= }}</ref> The [[Department of Defense Architecture Framework]] ([[DoDAF]]) suggests the use of the [[Operational View#Operational Activity Model|Operational Activity Model (OV-5)]] in conducting a CGA.<ref>"Department of Defense Architecture Framework", Version 1.5, Volume 2, [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]], 15 August 2003 [http://www.defenselink.mil/cio-nii/docs/DoDAF_Volume_II.pdf]</ref>
